**SUMMARY**: 
Calibrate to Lowest Opioid Dose Needed for Expected Results 
and Exercise Care When Changing Opioid Dosages 

**DETAILS**:
When opioid therapy is considered appropriate, calibrate opioid 
dosages to lowest dose needed to achieve expected effects and 
optimize nonopioid therapies. For patients already receiving opioid 
therapy, carefully weigh benefits and risks and exercise care when 
changing 
opioid dosage.

For guidance in determining the lowest effective opioid dosage, 
see [[https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/volumes/71/rr/rr7103a1.htm#Recommendation4 Recommendation 4 of the 2022 CDC Clinical Practice Guideline]].

For patients who have received opioid therapy for longer durations 
of time (e.g., for â‰¥1 year), if tapering, consider working closely 
with the patient to gradually taper dosages (no more than 10% 
per month).

For more guidance regarding tapering,  
see [[https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/volumes/71/rr/rr7103a1.htm#Recommendation5 Recommendation 5 of the 2022 CDC Clinical Practice Guideline]].

For a tapering calculator, see
[[https://agencymeddirectors.wa.gov/Calculator/TaperDoseCalculator.html Agency Medical Directors' Group (AMDG) MME Calculator]]

See [[index.html#morphine-milligram-equivalent-mme-calculation-cautions MME Calculator Cautions]].

